<DESCRIPT>  WOMAN; GAME; PROFESSIONAL; DEATH; OBITUARY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Ethel Cannon Sherard, affectionately known as "the Scrabble lady" and author
of a popular word book for players of the board game, has died. She was 95.;  
 Ms. Sherard died June 30 at Huntington Memorial Hospital, her daughter,
Gwendolyn Sherard-Bishop, said Monday.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ETHEL SHERARD, 95, 'THE SCRABBLE LADY'  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Obituaries  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     A longtime Scrabble expert, she continued to play in regional tournaments
despite failing health, and won a tourney in <LOCATION>Riverside</LOCATION> four years ago.;    At
age 84, <PERSON>Ms. Sherard</PERSON> published The Double List Word Book, a reference work of
100,000 words for use by <ORGANIZATION>Scrabble</ORGANIZATION> and crossword puzzle fans. The book lists
words by size and common first and last letters.;    "The book might seem like
a lot of work to some people, but it didn't seem like work to me," <PERSON>Ms. Sherard</PERSON>
said earlier this year. "I've always liked word games and taking big words and
finding small words in them.";    <PERSON>Ms. Sherard</PERSON> started playing Scrabble in the
<DATE>1930s</DATE>, when it was known as Criss-Cross. The title changed to <ORGANIZATION>Scrabble</ORGANIZATION> in
<DATE>1948</DATE>. The game's premise is to form interlocking words in crossword fashion
across a 225-square grid and score points.;    "She bought it for us as a
Christmas gift one year and the family began playing it," her daughter said.
"We started buying all kinds of dictionaries so we could have more words.
Everything went from there.";    <PERSON>Ms. Sherard</PERSON> frequently served as a word judge
at national Scrabble tournaments. She celebrated her 95th birthday in <DATE>January</DATE>
playing in a Scrabble contest at <LOCATION>Pasadena City College.</LOCATION>;    Born in <LOCATION>La Grange</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Ga.</LOCATION>, in <DATE>1896</DATE>, <PERSON>Ms. Sherard</PERSON> graduated from <LOCATION>Atlanta University</LOCATION>. She operated a
grocery store in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> and worked as a clerk with the federal government.;  
 She later moved to <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> and was a resident of the <ORGANIZATION>Eagle Rock</ORGANIZATION> area of
<LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> when she died. Her husband, <PERSON>Benjamin Sherard</PERSON>, died five years
ago.;    In addition to daughter, <PERSON>Gwendolyn</PERSON>, of <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Ms. Sherard</PERSON> is
survived by a son, <PERSON>Edgar Sherard</PERSON>, of <PERSON>Gary</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Ind.</LOCATION>; eight grandchildren; and 13
great-grandchildren.;    Funeral services were scheduled today at <ORGANIZATION>Cedar Park
Cemetery</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>.  </TEXT>
