<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 94 / Battle for Scrabble maker reopened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The battle for control of <ORGANIZATION>JW Spear</ORGANIZATION>, the maker of the '<ORGANIZATION>Scrabble</ORGANIZATION>' board game,
was thrown open again yesterday when a High Court judge released the
company's trustees from any obligation to sell their shares to <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>, the
US toy group.
The judge ruled that <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION>, a rival US toy company, had acted properly in
announcing an improved offer five minutes before the deadline for the
operation of a clause allowing the trustees to be released from an
irrevocable undertaking to sell a controlling interest to <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>.
The court's decision now leaves the Spear trustees - who own 24.9 per cent
of the company - free to accept the <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> bid or any higher one.
<ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> was <TIME>last night</TIME> considering its options: to mount an appeal against
the ruling, out-bid <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION>, or walk away. The company is certain to reach
its decision before <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, after which an undertaking given yesterday by
the trustees not to sell their shares to anyone else will expire.
The dispute arose after the Spear trustees gave irrevocable undertakings on
<DATE>May 27</DATE> to accept a Pounds 46.9m bid from <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> which, with 26.7 per cent,
has been the largest shareholder outside the <PERSON>Spear</PERSON> family for the past four
years. However, <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> responded with a Pounds 52m bid. This was announced
at five minutes to <TIME>midnight</TIME> on <DATE>June 2</DATE>, the final day when the escape clause
applied to allow the trustees to accept higher bids.
The legal action centred on whether <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> had fulfilled its obligations to
make a public announcement of its offer. <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> had informed the <ORGANIZATION>Stock
Exchange</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Takeover Panel</ORGANIZATION> in the minutes leading up to the final
deadline, but not the national press.
Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> argued that the offer should also have been announced to
at least two national newspapers and two UK wire services.
Giving judgment, <PERSON>Mr Justice Chadwick</PERSON> said that when the escape clause was
agreed between <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> and the trustees, it was likely that their intention
was to guarantee the commitment of third-party bidders rather than informing
the investing public.
Spear, its trustees and <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> welcomed yesterday's outcome.
</TEXT>
