<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / (CORRECTED) UK Company News: Hasbro gives up on Spear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 14th <DATE>July 1994</DATE>) appended to this article.
Hasbro yesterday threw in its hand in the battle for JW Spear, the maker of
<ORGANIZATION>Scrabble</ORGANIZATION>, and said it would accept the Pounds 11.50 a share bid from US toy
rival <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION>.
It described the Pounds 62m offer as 'very generous and above a level which
we could justify in business terms'.
The decision ends a fierce scrap over <LOCATION>Spear</LOCATION>, which started when <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>
launched a 900p a share bid for the company at the end of <DATE>May</DATE>. It had held a
26.7 per cent stake since <DATE>1990</DATE> and had received undertakings from the
trustees of some <PERSON>Spear</PERSON> family trusts to sell their 24.9 per cent stake
unless a higher offer was received within three working days.
After a frantic search for a white knight, <ORGANIZATION>Hambro</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Spear</ORGANIZATION>'s merchant bank,
persuaded <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> to launch a rival bid at Pounds 10 a share five minutes
before the deadline. Hasbro came back with an Pounds 11 a share offer last
<DATE>Friday</DATE>, which was topped by <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>.
<PERSON>Mr Norman Walker</PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro International</ORGANIZATION>, said: 'Our offer at
Pounds 11 per share was a very full one which we are not prepared to
increase. We are very pleased at the outcome for all shareholders and will
of course realise a substantial gain on our own investment which we made in
<DATE>1990</DATE>.' Hasbro bought its original stake at under Pounds 3 a share.
The outcome leaves the rights to Scrabble divided between <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>,
which are fierce rivals in the doll market. <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>, maker of <LOCATION>Sindy</LOCATION>, retains
the rights to Scrabble in <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION>, leaving <ORGANIZATION>Barbie</ORGANIZATION>'s creator, <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION>,
with the rest of the world.
<ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION>'s victory is particularly sweet for <PERSON>Robert Fleming</PERSON>, the merchant
bank. It was appointed by <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION> just six hours before the initial offer had
to be launched and completed the task with a few minutes to spare.
CORRECTION
JW Spear's merchant bank, which handled its successful sale to <ORGANIZATION>Mattel</ORGANIZATION>,
was <PERSON>Barings</PERSON> not Hambros as stated yesterday.
</TEXT>
