<DATELINE> TORONTO  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Chieftain Products Inc.</ORGANIZATION> said it is suing <LOCATION>West Hartford</LOCATION>, Conn.-based <ORGANIZATION>Coleco Industries Inc.</ORGANIZATION> in the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Ontario</LOCATION> for alleged violation of a contractual agreement to market Scrabble and other game products in <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>. 

   Chieftain, based in <LOCATION>Downsview</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ontario</LOCATION>, said it seeks an injunction to prevent <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Canada) Ltd.</ORGANIZATION> unit from selling Scrabble in <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>, beginning in <DATE>April</DATE>. 
Chieftain has been selling Scrabble in <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> since <DATE>1980</DATE>, and claims that it signed an agreement with <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1986</DATE> that provided for extension of the marketing arrangement beyond <DATE>April</DATE>. 

   A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> said that a letter of intent to extend the original agreement was signed in <DATE>September 1986</DATE>, but that the letter was subject to a full agreement, which <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> says never took place. 
The spokesman further said that <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> informed Chieftain in <DATE>December 1986</DATE> that <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> intended to market Scrabble on its own. 
<ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> "will vigorously contest" the suit, the spokesman said. 

   Closely held <LOCATION>Chieftain</LOCATION> is seeking <MONEY>$15 million</MONEY> in damages related to the alleged breach of contract. 

</TEXT>
