<HEAD>Hasbro Earnings Rise 73 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toy company <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro Inc.</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> said
better profit margins and improved performances by its <PERSON>Milton
Bradley</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Playskool</ORGANIZATION> units helped <DATE>third-quarter</DATE> earnings rise <PERCENT>73
percent</PERCENT>.
   The company reported earnings of <MONEY>$31.3 million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>53 cents</MONEY> per
share, compared with <MONEY>$18.08 million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>31 cents</MONEY> a share, in <DATE>1988's
third quarter</DATE>. Revenue rose <PERCENT>9.4 percent</PERCENT> to <MONEY>$403 million</MONEY> in the
<DATE>quarter ended Sept. 30</DATE> from <MONEY>$368.4 million</MONEY> a year earlier.
   ``As anticipated, our <DATE>third quarter</DATE> gross profit margin improved
from that of the <DATE>second quarter</DATE>,'' said <PERSON>Alan G. Hassenfeld</PERSON>,
chairman and chief executive.
   Along with better revenue by <PERSON>Milton Bradley</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Playskool</ORGANIZATION>, which
concentrates on toys for infants and young children, international
operations showed improvement, despite being hurt by a strong
dollar, <PERSON>Hassenfeld</PERSON> said.
   Analysts had said the <PERSON>Milton Bradley</PERSON> unit's board games could
take a beating from video games.
   Hasbro recently bought many of the products formerly
manufactured by <ORGANIZATION>Coleco Industries Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, including Cabbage Patch
dolls, <ORGANIZATION>Scrabble</ORGANIZATION> and Parcheesi.
   These additions plus a new line of battery powered racing cars
called <ORGANIZATION>Record Breakers</ORGANIZATION> places <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> in a good position to enter
the Christmas buying season, <PERSON>Hassenfeld</PERSON> said.
   For the first nine months of this year, <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> earned <MONEY>$68.2
million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>$1.15</MONEY> a share, up nearly <PERCENT>33 percent</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$51.3 million</MONEY>,
or <MONEY>88 cents</MONEY> a share, a year earlier. Revenue totaled <MONEY>$992.7
million</MONEY>, about <PERCENT>3 percent</PERCENT> higher than <MONEY>$962.9 million</MONEY> in <DATE>1988</DATE>.
</TEXT>
