<HEAD>Coleco Nearing Sale to Hasbro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro Inc.</ORGANIZATION> officials declined comment
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE> on published reports that <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>, the world's biggest
toymaker, would buy most of <ORGANIZATION>Coleco Industries Inc.</ORGANIZATION> under a plan to
be presented in bankruptcy court.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Hartford Courant</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> that sources close to
Avon-based <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s 10-month-old bankruptcy case told the newspaper
that details of the plan still were being negotiated.
   <PERSON>Barry Alperin</PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, declined
to comment on the report, saying the companies were forbidden from
discussing the case in public by an order last month from <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
Bankruptcy Court in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>.
   A secretary for <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, <PERSON>Morton Handel</PERSON>, said he would
be away from his office all day. She declined to say where he could
be contacted.
   Representatives of <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s creditors are
scheduled to appear <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in bankruptcy court in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to
discuss the plan.
   The deal expected to be announced <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> would strengthen
<ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>'s position in the toy business by adding such well-known
<ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> items as Cabbage Patch Kids and Scrabble and Parcheesi board
games to its product lines.
   While many details are unknown, sources told The Courant that
the deal would provide that:
   _Much of <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> would be sold to <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>, but it could not be
determined whether <LOCATION>Pawtucket</LOCATION>, R.I.-based company would buy all of
<ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> or just most of its assets. If <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> is sold, it would end
57 years as an independent company.
   _<ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s committee of unsecured creditors would drop its <MONEY>$71
million</MONEY> lawsuit against the company's largest creditors, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>
businessmen <PERSON>Isaac Perlmutter</PERSON> and <PERSON>Bernard Marden</PERSON>.
   _<PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> and <PERSON>Marden</PERSON>, in turn, would reduce their <MONEY>$80 million</MONEY>
claim against <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> by an undetermined amount.
   The lawsuit contends that <PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> and <PERSON>Marden</PERSON>, who are secured
creditors, cheated <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> out of <MONEY>millions of dollars</MONEY> through a
complex scheme of trading television advertising time for products.
   The deal would be a victory for <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s unsecured creditors,
because a reduced claim by <PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> and <PERSON>Marden</PERSON> means more money
would be available to repay them, the newspaper said. <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> had
debts of <MONEY>$540.3 million</MONEY> when it filed for protection from its
creditors under the bankruptcy laws in <DATE>July</DATE>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> grew to be one of the nation's largest toy companies
during the past decade, propelled in large part by its Cabbage
Patch Kids dolls.
   But demand for the dolls dropped beginning in <DATE>1986</DATE> and <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>
was not successful at introducing new products to make up for the
lost sales. The company sought Bankruptcy Court protection last
year.
   <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> filed its first reorganization plan in late <DATE>January</DATE>,
detailing how it planned to repay creditors. But that proposal
immediately was rejected by the creditors' committee, which said it
provided inadequate payment and appeared to favor <PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> and
<PERSON>Marden</PERSON>'s interests over the committee's.
   The plan would have given <PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Marden</ORGANIZATION> <PERCENT>55 percent</PERCENT> of
the stock of a reorganized <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> and a note for <MONEY>$40 million</MONEY> in
cash. Creditors would have received about <PERCENT>36 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>
stock and no cash, a plan they valued at about <MONEY>5 cents</MONEY> for every <MONEY>$1</MONEY>
they are owed.
   In <DATE>March</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> said it was considering selling the company
outright to resolve its financial problems.
   A few weeks later, however, the company reversed itself and said
it would instead propose a new reorganization plan offering a
larger repayment to creditors, consisting of about <MONEY>10 cents</MONEY> for
every <MONEY>$1</MONEY> of debt, plus <PERCENT>37 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s stock.
   <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> had not yet filed that new plan with the <ORGANIZATION>Bankruptcy Court</ORGANIZATION>
when creditors announced <DATE>April 19</DATE> that they had negotiated a deal
to sell most of <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> for more than <MONEY>$85 million</MONEY> in cash.
</TEXT>
