<HEAD>Coleco Creditors Outline Plan For Settling Lawsuits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes cycle designator, deletes day from lead.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Coleco Industries Inc.</ORGANIZATION> creditors say they have
agreed to settle lawsuits stemming from the troubled toymaker's
11-month bankruptcy case.
   The settlement, announced <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> during a hearing in <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
Bankruptcy Court, must be approved by the court.
   Meanwhile, no details were released about a proposal by <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro
Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest toy manufacturer, to purchase most of
<ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON>Daniel Golden</PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>, said
negotiations concerning the sale of most <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> assets continued.
   <PERSON>Richard Tilton</PERSON>, a lawyer for <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>, said he expected a joint
statement on the proposed sale would be issued next week. He
declined to discuss details of the plan, saying it still was
``subject to a number of conditions that need to be discussed.''
   The creditors' settlement announced <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> calls for <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s
largest creditors, <PERSON>Isaac Perlmutter</PERSON> and <PERSON>Bernard Marden</PERSON>, to receive
<MONEY>$61 million</MONEY> of their <MONEY>$87 million</MONEY> claim against <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>.
   Unsecured creditors of the company based in <LOCATION>Avon</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Conn.</LOCATION>, would
drop their <MONEY>$71 million</MONEY> lawsuit against <PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> and <PERSON>Marden</PERSON>, under
the settlement.
   The unsecured creditors had claimed that <PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> and <PERSON>Marden</PERSON>,
secured creditors, cheated <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> out of <MONEY>millions of dollars</MONEY>
through a complex scheme of trading television advertising time for
products.
   <PERSON>Tilton</PERSON> said the settlement would mean that <PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> could not
finance <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s reorganization plan as originally intended. But
<PERSON>Tilton</PERSON> said alternative sources of funding could be found. He did
not elaborate.
   <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>, which grew to be one of the nation's largest toymakers
during the past decade, suffered a change in fortune in <DATE>1986</DATE>, when
demand for its Cabbage Patch dolls dropped.
   New lines introduced by the company failed to make up for lost
sales, and <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> sought Bankruptcy Court protection last <DATE>July</DATE>,
citing debts of <MONEY>$540.3 million</MONEY>.
   A first reorganization plan filed by <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>January</DATE> was
rejected immediately by the creditors' committee.
   The plan would have given <PERSON>Perlmutter</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Marden</ORGANIZATION> <PERCENT>55 percent</PERCENT> of
the stock of a reorganized <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> and a note for <MONEY>$40 million</MONEY> in
cash. Creditors would have received about <PERCENT>36 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>
stock and no cash, a plan they valued at about <MONEY>5 cents</MONEY> for every <MONEY>$1</MONEY>
they are owed.
   In <DATE>March</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> said it was considering a sale of the company,
but reversed itself a few weeks later, filing a new reorganization
plan it hoped would satisfy creditors.
   The new plan offered a larger repayment, including about <MONEY>10
cents</MONEY> for every <MONEY>$1</MONEY> of debt, plus <PERCENT>37 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s stock.
   On <DATE>April 19</DATE>, before the second plan was filed with the
<ORGANIZATION>Bankruptcy Court</ORGANIZATION>, creditors announced they had negotiated a deal to
sell most of <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> for more than <MONEY>$85 million</MONEY> in cash.
   The deal would add well-known <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> items such as the Cabbage
Patch Kids and Scrabble and Parcheesi board games to <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>'s
product lines, it has been reported.
   <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> officials, upset by the <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> proposal, asked <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
Bankruptcy <PERSON>Judge Prudence B. Abram</PERSON> on <DATE>April 20</DATE> to issue a
restraining order prohibiting creditors from pursuing the plan with
<ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>.
   Instead, <PERSON>Abram</PERSON> urged the two sides to strike a compromise.
</TEXT>
