<LP>
   PAWTUCKET, R.I. -- Hasbro Inc. said net income rose 61% in
the fourth quarter, reflecting a 54% increase in revenue
buoyed by healthy Christmas sales and contributions from its
acquisition last year of Tonka Corp.
   Hasbro, the nation's largest toy and game maker, posted
net of $44.8 million, or 76 cents a share, compared with
$27.9 million, or 49 cents a share, a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Fourth-quarter revenue of <MONEY>$761.2 million</MONEY>, up from <MONEY>$492.8
million</MONEY> in the <DATE>1990 fourth quarter</DATE>, included <MONEY>$202 million</MONEY>
from <ORGANIZATION>Tonka</ORGANIZATION>; excluding <ORGANIZATION>Tonka</ORGANIZATION>, revenue still grew a healthy
<PERCENT>13%</PERCENT>.
   "Hasbro finished up for the year in strong fashion, and
its results are right in line with expectations," said
analyst <PERSON>Gary M. Jacobson</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co</ORGANIZATION>. He pointed
out that the company's earnings were depressed in the <DATE>1990
fourth quarter</DATE> because of write-offs from several toy
retailers -- including <ORGANIZATION>Child World Inc.</ORGANIZATION> -- that were having
difficulties.
   "The integration of {<ORGANIZATION>Tonka</ORGANIZATION>} operations is now
substantially complete, and we expect they will be a positive
contributing factor to the combined operations in <DATE>1992</DATE>," said
<PERSON>Alan G. Hassenfeld</PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer.
   <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> was helped by the Christmas sales successes of
Go-Go My Walking Pup, <ORGANIZATION>Scrabble</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Electronic Hotshot Basketball</ORGANIZATION>
and the revitalized G.I. <PERSON>Joe</PERSON> line.
   Net for the year was <MONEY>$81.7 million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>$1.41</MONEY> a share, on
revenue of <MONEY>$2.14 billion</MONEY> after a pretax restructuring charge
of <MONEY>$59 million</MONEY> recorded in the <DATE>second quarter</DATE> for the <ORGANIZATION>Tonka</ORGANIZATION>
purchase. In <DATE>1990</DATE>, the company had net of <MONEY>$89.2 million</MONEY>, or
<MONEY>$1.54</MONEY> a share, on revenue of <MONEY>$1.52 billion</MONEY>.
   The company's growth is increasingly coming from its
international business, which now accounts for about <PERCENT>40%</PERCENT> of
revenue. While domestic revenue rose about <PERCENT>40%</PERCENT> in the <DATE>fourth
quarter</DATE> from a year earlier, international revenue was about
<PERCENT>70%</PERCENT> higher, said <PERSON>John O'Neill</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>'s chief financial
officer.
</TEXT>
