<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the <ORGANIZATION>Securities and Exchange
Commission</ORGANIZATION> and the top federal prosecutor of insider trading have
endorsed legislation that would make brokerage firms liable when
employees violate securities laws.
   However, <ORGANIZATION>SEC</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>David S. Ruder</PERSON> and <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON>Rudolph
W. Giuliani</PERSON> cautioned <DATE>Monday</DATE> that the law should exempt firms and
supervisors that make a good-faith effort to prevent their
employees from using non-public information to profit from trading
in securities.
   They said a draft bill offered by Rep. <PERSON>Edward J. Markey</PERSON>,
<LOCATION>D-Mass.</LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION>House Energy and Commerce</ORGANIZATION> finance
subcommittee, should more carefully spell out when brokerage firms
would be subject to fines for the violations of their employees.
</TEXT>
