<HEAD>Hasbro Completes Purchase of Coleco Inc.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CHANGE dateline to conform with style,
ADD in 2nd graf that Hasbro is based in Pawtucket.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro Inc.</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> it had
completed the purchase of most of the product lines of financially
troubled <ORGANIZATION>Coleco Industries Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, and would immediately begin
producing the popular Cabbage Patch Kids dolls.
   <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest toymaker, agreed last week to
purchase <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s major assets for <MONEY>$85 million</MONEY> cash and an option
for <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> to purchase 1 million shares of Pawtucket-based <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> at
<MONEY>$28.85</MONEY> each after its bankruptcy reorganization plan was confirmed,
said <PERSON>Barry Alperin</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>'s executive vice president.
   Conneticut-based <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION> filed for protection from its creditors
under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy act a year ago, citing
debts of <MONEY>$540.3 million</MONEY>.
   Hasbro stock closed at <MONEY>$20</MONEY> <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> on the <ORGANIZATION>American Stock
Exchange</ORGANIZATION>, down <MONEY>25 cents</MONEY> a share.
   <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION> said it had reached agreement with <ORGANIZATION>Appalachian Artworks
Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, creator of <ORGANIZATION>Cabbage Patch Kids</ORGANIZATION>, to begin manufacturing the
dolls immediately, in time to advertise them for <DATE>Christmas</DATE>.
   The dolls would be made overseas and packaged at <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Milton
Bradley</PERSON> division in <LOCATION>East Longmeadow</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Alperin</PERSON> said. Most of
<ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s other lines, including the Scrabble and Parcheesi games
also would be produced in <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>, which also bought the right to use <ORGANIZATION>Coleco</ORGANIZATION>'s name, would
discontinue some of its products, including Alf and Wrinkles,
<PERSON>Alperin</PERSON> said.
   Chairman <PERSON>Alan G. Hassenfeld</PERSON> said the acquisition would add ``some
time-tested products which will enrich <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>'s three divisions
without material additions to our cost structure.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Hasbro</ORGANIZATION>'s third division is Playskool.
   <PERSON>Alperin</PERSON> said the Cabbage Patch line, which was the largest
selling toy of all time in <DATE>1985</DATE>, ``has not had the attention it
deserved over the past couple of years.''
   Sales of Cabbage Patch peaked at more than <MONEY>$600 million</MONEY> in <DATE>1985</DATE>
but slipped to <MONEY>$58 million</MONEY> by last year.
</TEXT>
